---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Panama Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/panama/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'Panama Pensionado Visa', href: '/visas/retirement-visa/in/panama' },
  { title: 'Insurance with Pre-existing Conditions', href: '/insurance-for/pre-existing-conditions' },
  { title: 'Costa Rica for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/costa-rica' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'panamaFit', header: 'Panama Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$380-520/mo', panamaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$460-660/mo', panamaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'GeoBlue (Americans)', entryAge: '84', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$400-560/mo', panamaFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: '80', monthlyFrom: '$300-420/mo', panamaFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'ASSA (Local)', entryAge: '65', renewal: '75', monthlyFrom: '$180-350/mo', panamaFit: 'Good (Local)' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$360-520', annual: '$4,320-6,240' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: '$500-720', annual: '$6,000-8,640' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: '$680-980', annual: '$8,160-11,760' },
  { category: 'Panamanian Private Insurance', monthly: '$150-400', annual: '$1,800-4,800' },
  { category: 'CSS Public (if eligible)', monthly: '~$80-120', annual: '$960-1,440' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Panama | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Panama. Pensionado visa, senior discounts, private hospitals, and coverage options for expats 70+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Panama"
  subheadline="Panama's famous Pensionado program, US dollar economy, and modern Panama City healthcare make it a premier retirement destination."
  heroImage="/images/countries/panama-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Panama</h2>
  <p>
    Panama has cultivated one of the world's most senior-friendly retirement environments. The Pensionado visa program offers substantial discounts on everything from flights to medical care, while the US dollar as currency eliminates exchange rate concerns for American retirees.
  </p>

  <p>
    Panama City offers first-world infrastructure with modern hospitals, international banking, and familiar American chains. Outside the capital, Boquete in the highlands attracts retirees seeking cooler mountain climate, while the Pacific beaches offer laid-back coastal living. The country's stability, low taxes, and established expat communities have made it a retirement hub for over two decades.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Currency:</strong> US Dollar (no exchange risk)</li>
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Modern private hospitals in Panama City</li>
      <li><strong>Senior discounts:</strong> Extensive Pensionado benefits</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Tropical lowlands; cooler highlands (Boquete)</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> $2,000-3,500/month comfortable lifestyle</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Panama's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Panama offers both public (CSS) and private healthcare. Most expats use private healthcare, which is modern and affordable compared to US prices, though not as inexpensive as some other Latin American countries.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Healthcare (Recommended)</h3>
  <p>
    Panama City has several JCI-accredited hospitals with US-trained doctors. Major facilities include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Hospital Punta Pacífica:</strong> Johns Hopkins-affiliated; top facility in Central America</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital Nacional:</strong> Large, modern full-service hospital</li>
    <li><strong>Centro Médico Paitilla:</strong> Established private hospital</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital Santa Fe:</strong> Modern facility with good reputation</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Private healthcare costs run 40-60% less than US prices. A doctor visit costs $50-80, specialist consultations $80-150, and even complex surgeries are significantly cheaper.
  </p>

  <h3>Public Healthcare (CSS)</h3>
  <p>
    The Caja de Seguro Social (CSS) provides public healthcare to those who contribute to the system. Retirees generally cannot join CSS unless they work or have a Panamanian spouse. Most expat seniors rely on private healthcare or international insurance.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Healthcare Outside Panama City</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      While Panama City has excellent hospitals, healthcare in areas like Boquete, Bocas del Toro, or beach communities is more limited. Basic care is available locally, but serious conditions require travel to Panama City. International insurance with evacuation coverage is important if you're living outside the capital.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Senior Retirees</h2>
  <p>
    Panama's Pensionado (Jubilado) visa is one of the most generous retirement visa programs in the world, offering extensive discounts and benefits.
  </p>

  <h3>Pensionado Visa (Jubilado)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Income requirement:</strong> $1,000/month from pension or retirement account</li>
    <li><strong>Age requirement:</strong> Must receive pension (no minimum age)</li>
    <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> Not strictly required but recommended</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Permanent residency from start</li>
    <li><strong>Spouse/dependents:</strong> Can be included with additional $250/month per dependent</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Pensionado Benefits (Jubilado Discounts)</h3>
  <p>
    The Pensionado visa includes remarkable discounts:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Medical consultations:</strong> 15% off doctor visits</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital services:</strong> 15% off hospital bills</li>
    <li><strong>Medications:</strong> 10-15% off prescriptions</li>
    <li><strong>Airline tickets:</strong> 25% off domestic, 15% international</li>
    <li><strong>Hotels:</strong> 50% off weekdays, 30% weekends</li>
    <li><strong>Restaurants:</strong> 25% off (select establishments)</li>
    <li><strong>Utilities:</strong> Discounts on electricity, phone, water</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Friendly Nations Visa</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Eligibility:</strong> Citizens of 50 "friendly" countries (includes US, UK, EU)</li>
    <li><strong>Requirements:</strong> Economic ties to Panama (job, business, or real estate)</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Permanent residency</li>
    <li><strong>Notes:</strong> No pension required; more flexible for younger retirees</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Planning Your Panama Retirement?"
    description="Get coverage that works with Panama's healthcare system."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Panama doesn't strictly require health insurance for the Pensionado visa, but having coverage is essential given the lack of public healthcare access for most retirees.
  </p>

  <h3>Visa Application</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Health insurance not mandatory for Pensionado visa</li>
    <li>Some immigration lawyers recommend showing coverage</li>
    <li>Friendly Nations visa may require financial stability proof</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Why Insurance Matters in Panama</h3>
  <p>
    Without CSS access, seniors must pay out-of-pocket or have private/international insurance. While Panama healthcare is affordable, a major illness or surgery can still cost $20,000-50,000+. Insurance provides:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Access to best private hospitals without financial stress</li>
    <li>Medical evacuation to US if needed</li>
    <li>Coverage when traveling outside Panama</li>
    <li>Protection against catastrophic medical costs</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Recommended Coverage Strategy</h3>
  <p>
    Given Panama's affordable private healthcare, many seniors opt for high-deductible international plans ($2,500-5,000 deductible). This keeps premiums lower while protecting against major expenses. Use the Pensionado discounts for routine care paid out-of-pocket.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Providers for Panama</h2>
  <p>
    These insurers work well for seniors retiring in Panama:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>GeoBlue (For Americans)</h3>
  <p>
    Accepts applicants up to age 84—crucial for older seniors. BCBS network access when visiting the US. Excellent option for Americans who maintain ties to the US and want seamless coverage in both countries.
  </p>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Top-tier international coverage with direct billing at Hospital Punta Pacífica (Johns Hopkins affiliate) and other major facilities. Entry up to 74 with lifetime renewal. Strong regional network throughout Latin America.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    Accepts applicants up to 79. Comprehensive coverage and excellent service. Premium pricing but reliable for seniors needing coverage above age 74.
  </p>

  <h3>Panamanian Local Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Insurers like ASSA, MAPFRE Panama, and Aseguradora Mundial offer local plans. Lower costs than international insurance but age limits typically 60-65 for new policies. Coverage limited to Panama. Best for younger retirees or as supplementary coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Senior-Friendly Plans"
    description="Find coverage that works with Panama's Pensionado discounts."
    buttonText="See Options →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for seniors in Panama are reasonable given the quality of healthcare available:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Out-of-Pocket Healthcare Costs</h3>
  <p>
    With Pensionado discounts applied, private healthcare in Panama is affordable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Doctor visit:</strong> $40-70 (after 15% discount)</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $70-130 (after discount)</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital day:</strong> $200-400 private room</li>
    <li><strong>MRI:</strong> $300-500</li>
    <li><strong>Hip replacement:</strong> $12,000-18,000</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High deductible:</strong> Use $5,000+ deductible; pay routine care out-of-pocket</li>
    <li><strong>Use Pensionado discounts:</strong> 15% off medical bills adds up</li>
    <li><strong>Regional coverage:</strong> "Americas only" costs less than worldwide</li>
    <li><strong>Exclude US coverage:</strong> If not visiting US, save 20-30%</li>
    <li><strong>Annual payment:</strong> Most insurers offer 5-10% discount for yearly payment</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Routine Care in Panama City</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Carol, 71, needs annual checkup and bloodwork.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Visits private clinic with Pensionado discount. Doctor visit $50, comprehensive bloodwork $80. Total: $130 out-of-pocket. Below deductible—no insurance claim filed.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: Specialist at Johns Hopkins Affiliate</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Mike, 68, needs cardiac evaluation.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Goes to Hospital Punta Pacífica (Johns Hopkins affiliate). Cardiologist consultation + stress test + echocardiogram: $450. Cigna Global covers after $2,500 deductible. Direct billing—Mike tracks toward deductible.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Emergency Surgery</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Susan, 73, needs emergency gallbladder removal.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Surgery at Hospital Nacional. Total bill $8,500 (after Pensionado discount). BUPA Global covers $6,000 after deductible. Direct billing arranged.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Living in Boquete</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">John, 72, retires in highland town of Boquete.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Local clinic handles routine care. When he needs hip replacement, travels to Panama City (6-hour drive or 45-minute flight). Surgery at Centro Médico Paitilla: $15,000 covered by Cigna after deductible.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: Medical Evacuation to US</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Robert, 76, diagnosed with rare cancer needing specialized treatment.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> GeoBlue arranges evacuation to MD Anderson in Houston. Air ambulance + initial treatment coordination covered. Uses Medicare for US treatment. Total evacuation cost: $42,000 covered.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Senior Over 80</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Eleanor, 81, wants to move to Panama.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> GeoBlue accepts her at 81 ($1,100/month). Pensionado visa approved easily. Uses combination of out-of-pocket care with discounts plus GeoBlue for major expenses and US visits.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is health insurance required for the Pensionado visa?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">No, Panama's Pensionado visa doesn't require health insurance. However, since you won't have access to public healthcare (CSS), having private or international insurance is strongly recommended. The visa is primarily income-based ($1,000/month pension).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How much do Pensionado discounts save on healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Pensionado discounts include 15% off doctor visits and hospital bills, plus 10-15% off medications. For a $10,000 surgery, that's $1,500 saved. Annual routine care savings can be $500-1,000+. These discounts apply even when paying with insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">I'm 78—what are my options?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">GeoBlue accepts Americans up to 84. BUPA Global accepts applicants up to 79. These are your main international options. Panamanian local insurers typically stop accepting new applicants at 65. At 78, GeoBlue is likely your best option.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I use Medicare in Panama?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">No, US Medicare doesn't cover care outside the United States. You need separate coverage in Panama. GeoBlue is ideal for Americans because it provides BCBS network access when you visit the US, complementing your Medicare coverage during trips home.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Panama City healthcare really that good?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, Hospital Punta Pacífica is affiliated with Johns Hopkins and meets US standards. Several hospitals are JCI-accredited. Many doctors trained in the US and speak English. Panama City healthcare is considered among the best in Latin America.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about the US dollar in Panama?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Panama uses the US dollar as its currency (alongside the Balboa, which is pegged 1:1). This eliminates exchange rate risk for American retirees. Your pension, Social Security, and investments maintain their value without currency fluctuation concerns.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Panama?"
    description="Find insurance that maximizes your Pensionado benefits."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes. Panama visa requirements, Pensionado benefits, and healthcare costs change. Verify current requirements with Panama immigration authorities. Consider consulting an immigration lawyer and insurance broker specializing in Panama expat coverage.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
